b:["$","div",null,{"className":"prose","children":[["$","h2",null,{"children":"Who Should Choose Which?"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"The ideal user for each platform differs considerably. Make (Integromat) is best suited for power users, agencies, complex automations, making it a strong choice if you fall into any of these categories. Workato, meanwhile, shines for enterprises, IT departments, large scale integrations, which means it may be the better pick if your needs align with those use cases.\n\nFounded in 2012, Make (Integromat) describes itself as \"Visual platform for designing, building, and automating complex workflows.\" Workato, established in 2013, positions itself as \"Enterprise integration and automation platform with AI-powered recipes.\" Both platforms have been in the market for a similar duration, giving each ample time to refine their offerings and build a loyal user base."}]]}]
c:["$","div",null,{"className":"verdict-box","children":[["$","h2",null,{"children":"Our Verdict"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"After analyzing all the data, **Make (Integromat)** comes out slightly ahead in this comparison, thanks to higher user ratings (9.0 vs 8.0), availability of a free plan. However, this does not mean Workato is a poor choice — far from it. Workato excels in its own right, particularly for enterprises and IT departments.\n\nOur recommendation: if you value superior visual workflow builder, go with Make (Integromat). If top-tier enterprise security and compliance matters more to you, Workato is the way to go. Either way, both are solid platforms that have earned their place in the market."}]]}]
